Abstract

This study focuses on developing predictive models to estimate the number of mentions within the Global Database of Events, Language, and Tone (GDELT) dataset. GDELT is a comprehensive collection of global news and events, documented from various sources around the world. Leveraging big data and cloud computing technologies, we aim to gain valuable insights into trends of real-world events. Our study encompasses the following areas:

  • Predictive Modeling: Implementing and evaluating different machine learning models to accurately predict number of mentions.
  • Feature Importance: By determining the most influential factors that affects the mention counts, we aim to uncover patterns in global news dissemination
  • Big Data Integration: Utilization of cloud computing resources to manage and process the vast GDELT dataset efficiently.

Introduction

In this age of information, the volume of data that is generated daily is constantly increasing. According to the report of IDC (2017), the global data quantity is projected to reach 175 zettabytes by 2025. This vast information includes news data, which is crucial on shaping the views and understanding of the public about the worldwide events. There are uncountable events happening all of the time, and it is impossible to pay attention to everything. Instead, we would like to filter this to identify important news for our further attention.

The GDELT project is a prime example of this valuable data, collecting news data from broadcasts, print, and web sources globally. Currently, the GDELT project has a collection of quarter-billion data points, which makes it a rich repository for exploring global events and societal trends (GDELT, n.d.). Unlike older projects that could only work on the english language internet, GDELT 2.0, launched in 2015, uses real time translations to include 65 foreign languages and news published in those languages to the database.

However, a crucial aspect of analyzing the GDELT data lies in understanding the significance of specific events. There are three metrics in the GDELT to predict event importance; Number of Mentions, Sources, and Articles. For this study, we aim to predict the number of mentions to better reflect not only the articles that specifically talk about this event, but also to capture related events that reference this event. This would allow us to predict and understand global developments and to identify key features that could be driving these mentions which would provide a deeper understanding of global news patterns.

Problem Statement

Can we create a machine learning model to predict the number of mentions that a news event will have and use this model to explain the impact of event characteristics on the number of mentions of the event as a proxy for the importance of an event?

Motivation

The ability to predict and analyze the number of mentions in global news can help improve the flow of information, identify emerging trends, and improve decisionmaking in domains such as public policy and business strategy. By leveraging big data and cloud computing, this project seeks to use the rich data of GDELT to provide actionable insights for data-driven decision making. The outcome of this project will not only contribute to academic knowledge but also offer practical benefits for the stakeholders that relies on timely and relevant news data.

Data Decription

Data Source

We obtained data from the GDELT project website, which is also acessible through the Amazon Web Services (AWS) Open Data Registry. We copied the data to our Amazon S3 bucket for further analysis. The raw GDELT dataset has a total of 64.9 gigabytes as seen in the screenshot below.

Data Scope and Limitations

For this project, we focused on a subset of the GDELT dataset. The analysis was conducted only using data from July 2016 to July 2019. In addition, we only considered several features for our analysis, namely:

  • GoldsteinScale
  • Actor1Code_ind
  • Actor1Name_ind
  • Actor1CountryCode_ind
  • Actor1Type1Code_ind
  • IsRootEvent_ind
  • EventCode_ind
  • EventBaseCode_ind
  • EventRootCode_ind
  • QuadClass_ind

These columns were chosen based on their relevance to predicting the number of mentions and understanding the significance of events. The dataset's temporal scope and the limited number of columns represent potential constraints on the comprehensiveness of our analysis. In addition, we performed the analysis using AWS EMR cluster with configuration of 1 primary and 19 cores of m5.xlarge as shown in the screenshot below.

Data Overview

The GDELT (Global Database of Events, Language, and Tone) dataset is a comprehensive, open-source dataset that records global events and their attributes. This dataset is used to predict the number of mentions of events and explore the features influencing these mentions. Table 1 shows the overview of the description of the columns within the original GDELT dataset.

Table 1. Original GDELT Data Overview

Column Description Column Description
GLOBALEVENTID Unique identifier for each event. EventBaseCode The base CAMEO event code.
SQLDATE The date of the event in YYYYMMDD format. EventRootCode The root CAMEO event code.
Actor1Code The code for the first actor involved in the event. QuadClass The CAMEO quad class of the event, categorizing it into one of four categories: Verbal Cooperation, Material Cooperation, Verbal Conflict, or Material Conflict.
Actor1Name The name of the first actor involved in the event. GoldsteinScale A numeric score measuring the impact of the event. Positive values indicate cooperative events, while negative values indicate conflict events.
Actor1CountryCode The country code of the first actor involved in the event. NumMentions The number of mentions of the event across sources.
Actor1Type1Code The type code of the first actor involved in the event. NumSources The number of distinct sources reporting the event.
Actor2Code The code for the second actor involved in the event. NumArticles The number of distinct articles discussing the event.
Actor2Name The name of the second actor involved in the event. AvgTone The average tone of the coverage on the event, where higher values indicate more positive sentiment and lower values indicate more negative sentiment.
Actor2CountryCode The country code of the second actor involved in the event. Actor1Geo_Type The geographic type of the first actor involved in the event (e.g., country, city).
Actor2Type1Code The type code of the second actor involved in the event. Actor1Geo_FullName The full geographic name of the first actor's location.
IsRootEvent Indicates whether this event is the root event (1) or not (0). Actor1Geo_CountryCode The country code of the first actor's location.
EventCode The CAMEO event code describing the type of event. Actor1Geo_ADM1Code The administrative division code of the first actor's location.
Actor1Geo_Lat The latitude of the first actor's location. ActionGeo_Type The geographic type of the event's location (e.g., country, city).
Actor1Geo_Long The longitude of the first actor's location. ActionGeo_FullName The full geographic name of the event's location.
Actor1Geo_FeatureID The geographic feature ID of the first actor's location. ActionGeo_CountryCode The country code of the event's location.
Actor2Geo_Type The geographic type of the second actor involved in the event (e.g., country, city). ActionGeo_ADM1Code The administrative division code of the event's location.
Actor2Geo_FullName The full geographic name of the second actor's location. ActionGeo_Lat The latitude of the event's location.
Actor2Geo_CountryCode The country code of the second actor's location. ActionGeo_Long The longitude of the event's location.
Actor2Geo_ADM1Code The administrative division code of the second actor's location. ActionGeo_FeatureID The geographic feature ID of the event's location.
Actor2Geo_Lat The latitude of the second actor's location. DATEADDED The date the event was added to the GDELT database.
Actor2Geo_Long The longitude of the second actor's location. SOURCEURL The URL of the source article that reported the event.
Actor2Geo_FeatureID The geographic feature ID of the second actor's location.

Methodology

In[41]:
Image(filename="method.png", width=10000, height=250)
Out[41]:
Figure 1. Methodology Overview

Overview

The methodology for this project was structured into five main steps as shown in Figure 1.

  • Data Collection: The GDELT dataset was collected through the AWS Open Data Registry. The collected data was then transferred to an AWS S3 bucket for storage and further processing
  • Data Preprocessing: The raw data gone through cleaning and preprocessing to ensure its suitability for the models and our analysis. This step includes handling missing values, encoding variablesl, and normalizing numerical values.
  • Model Training: Various machine learning models were trained to predict the number of mentions in the GDELT dataset, namely linear regression, factorization machines, and random forest regression. Model optimization was performed using Grid Search to find the best parameters.
  • Model Evaluation. The performance of the models was evaluated using Mean Absolute Error (MAE) to ensure accuracy and reliability.
  • Feature Importance: To understand the significance of each feature in the machine learning models, feature importance analysis was conducted.

All of the tasks was done using Apache Spark to enable efficient handling and processing of the big dataset.

Detailed

Data Collection

The GDelt dataset was collected from its own public amazon s3 bucket and then transferred to our own S3 bucket. The dataset consists of 1,095 files in total, spanning the period from July 01, 2016, to July 01, 2019 (three years' worth of data). For a more detailed description of the data collection process, please refer to the file_transfer.ipynb file.

Once the data was collected, the first thing we did is to extract the necessary dataset from it. Since the data has no column name, we collected its column labels from GDELT Website. Once we were able to rename the dataset, we based the importance of the columns from the GDELT Data Format Documentation. Having chosen the appropriate columns needed for prediction, we selected those columns and dropped all of their null values. This resulted in a usable dataset in Parquet format. Table 2 shows the columns we expect to use.

Note: For a better extraction of the data, please see the data_extraction.ipynb file.

Table 2. Processed GDELT Data Overview

variables description
Actor1Code raw CAMEO code for Actor1
IsRootEvent a proxy for the rough importance of an event
Actor1Name The actual name of the Actor 1
EventCode This is the raw CAMEO action code describing the action that Actor1 performed
Actor1CountryCode The 3-character CAMEO code for the country affiliation of Actor1.
Actor1Type1Code CAMEO event codes are defined in a three-level taxonomy
EventRootCode defines the root-level category the event code falls under
GoldsteinScale Each CAMEO event code is assigned a numeric score from -10 to +10, capturing the theoretical potential impact that type of event will have on the stability of a country
QuadClass The entire CAMEO event taxonomy is ultimately organized under four primary classifications: Verbal Cooperation, Material Cooperation, Verbal Conflict, and Material Conflict.
NumMentions(target) This is the total number of mentions of this event across all source documents.

Data Preprocessing

As seen in the exploration, the columns: Actor1Code, Actor1Name, Actor1CountryCode, Actor1Type1Code, IsRootEvent, EventCode, EventBaseCode, EventRootCode, QuadClass has a string data typea. However, based on the GDELT Data Format Documentation, these columns should be treated as categorical. Therefore, we will apply StringIndexer to convert these column values to their respective indeces. Similarly, the GoldsteinScale and NumMentions should be treated sa double.

In[16]:
si = StringIndexer(inputCols=["Actor1Code", "Actor1Name", "Actor1CountryCode",
                             "Actor1Type1Code", "IsRootEvent", "EventCode",
                             "EventBaseCode", "EventRootCode", "QuadClass"], 
                   outputCols=["Actor1Code_ind", "Actor1Name_ind",
                               "Actor1CountryCode_ind", "Actor1Type1Code_ind",
                               "IsRootEvent_ind", "EventCode_ind",
                               "EventBaseCode_ind", "EventRootCode_ind",
                               'QuadClass_ind']);

VBox()
FloatProgress(value=0.0, bar_style='info', description='Progress:', layout=Layout(height='25px', width='50%'),

+-------+------------------+

Again, examining the summary of NumMentions after filtering for values greater than 10, we can still see a large gap. This indicates that NumMentions is highly right-skewed. To address the skewness of the target variable, we will apply a logarithmic transformation.

With the log transformation we were able to reduce the skewness of the dataset and can be used for now as a target variable for prediction.

*Applying vector assembler and min max scaler to the feature and target*

In Machine Learning of big data, the accepted column is on the form of vector, hence we will vectorize all feature columns so that we may be able to use the machine learning of big data, moreover to reduce the range of the the vector and target variable and avoid the impact of high index categories we will apply MinMaxScaler

Machine Learning Models

To predict the number of mentions in the GDELT dataset, we implemented two machine learning models: Linear Regression and Random Forest Regressor.

Linear Regression is a straightforward and interpretable model that can provide insights into the relationships between features and the target variable. Meanwhile, Random Forest Regression is known for its robustness and ability to handle non-linear data.

In[40]:
lr = LinearRegression(featuresCol="scaledFeatures",
                           labelCol="target");
rf = RandomForestRegressor(featuresCol="scaledFeatures",
                           labelCol="target");

To streamline the modeling process and ensure consistency, we created pipelines for each model. The pipelines integrate the models with the necessary preprocessing steps.

pipe_lr = Pipeline(stages=[lr]);

Hyperparameter Tuning with Grid Search

To optimize the performance of our models, we performed hyperparameter tuning using Grid Search. This process involves systematically varying the hyperparameters to find the best combination.

In[42]:
paramGrid_lr = (ParamGridBuilder()
             .addGrid(lr.elasticNetParam, [0, 1])
             .addGrid(lr.maxIter, [50, 100, 200, 500])
             .addGrid(lr.solver, ['auto', 'normal', 'l-bfgs'])
             .build());

paramGrid_rf = (ParamGridBuilder()
                .addGrid(rf.maxBins, [5, 15])
                .addGrid(rf.maxDepth, [5, 15])
                .addGrid(rf.featureSubsetStrategy, ['sqrt', 'log2'])
                .build());

Model Evaluation and Cross-Validation

To evaluate the performance of our models, we used the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) metric. Lower MAE values indicate better model performance. Also, to ensure the robustness of our model evaluations, we employed 3-fold cross-validation.

In[43]:
evaluator = RegressionEvaluator(labelCol="target",
                                predictionCol="prediction",
                                metricName='mae');

crossval_lr = CrossValidator(estimator=pipe_lr,
                          estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid_lr,
                          evaluator=evaluator,
                          numFolds=3);

crossval_rf = CrossValidator(estimator=pipe_rf,

Results and Discussion

Table 2. Summary of Model Results
Model Mean Absolute Error
Naive Baseline 13. 4198
Linear Regression 2. 9961
Random Forest Regression 2.8300
Table 3. Top 3 Most Important Feature
Feature Value
Actor1 Name 0.4513
Actor1 Country Code 0.1476
Actor1 Code 0.1146

Our study set the baseline Mean Average Error of 13.42 NumMentions based on the average count of NumMentions. Based on our exploratory data analysis, the range of NumMentions goes from 0 until values in the tens of thousands. Thus, we can confirm that the distribution of NumMentions is mostly focused on the low range of values less than 10 while the outliers with thousands or tens of thousands of mentions are significantly driving up the error but due to their relatively low number, total error seems small.

We then compare this to the results of the trained machine learning models of Random Forest and Linear Regression, which were able to achieve a mean average error of less than 3. This shows that our model was able to learn from the features available in the GDELT dataset to capture factors that drive the number of mentions for events. What we have observed is a better alignment to the floor NumMentions for items in general and a better capability of capturing outliers in NumMentions with very large counts compared to the rest of the events.

The Feature Importances for the best performing model were used to identify important columns with the data that contributes the most to our predictions. Since these columns were converted into string indexes in pyspark, they are ordered according to frequency in the original data, and so feature importances can be used to isolate the impact of frequency of a certain actor or event code and feature to the NumMentions. According to this, this shows that the frequency of an actor, which could also be related to the importance or newsworthiness of an actor, is quite highly correlated and impacts the number of mentions or news importance of an event. Likewise, this is true for the country code where events happening in countries with more events and most likely large populations that are interested in these events is more likely to be mentioned multiple times.

Conclusion

Based on the result, we are able to create a model that can predict the number of mentions with an average error of under 3. This is quite a good result with a significant improvement over the baseline with an average error of 13, and shows that the features that are in GDELT are actually able to capture important factors that affect news importance. The top three features that affect the number of mentions are isolated into the Actor1Name, Actor1CountryCode, and the Actor1Code. Since these are all string indexes, that means that it is the frequency of the item which is correlated with the importance of the event in the news. Most likely, this is because the most attention grabbing events and actors are also the most commonly covered and mentioned events. What is surprising is that the goldstein score which is meant to be a measurement of the impact of conflict or cooperation is very low on feature importance and has low predictive power of event importance.

Recommendation

For further studies we recommend some approaches that could enhance the training model and possibly improve the results.

  1. Data Cleaning and Feature Engineering can be approached now with more context. Since we know that frequency of the actor's names can affect the event's perceived importance, including actor2 columns but sharing their string index with actor1 columns could capture events done to high frequency or importance actors by unimportant or uncommon actors which would also trigger more mentions. Similarly, we can try to feature engineer the Event columns to bin and collect some similar kinds of events together based on their frequencies to reduce the number of unique event codes and create a more learnable feature for the models.
  2. Events are interrelated, and if we can capture if certain events in a sequence are related to high impact events, this could also improve the model results. This could be a kind of feature engineering where the number of mentions for events that are mentioned in an article are used as an input feature for its own NumMentions.
  3. The models used in this study are relatively simple and straightforward. By using more complex machine learning models such as Neural Networks, it may be possible to improve the results as well.
